entry.title: Best Practice for handling SUM log files
entry.content:
Background:

During the upgrade SUM generates log files. From the SUM guide, help docs and experiences I've learned, that...

  • SUM itself copies log files of past runs into a separate folder structure.
  • There's also some advice from SAP to cleanse old log files.

Now I wonder what is the actual best practice? How are you doing it?

I would assume...

  • the recently created or the older log files are taken off the fileshare and kept in a cheap storage location. Directly readable or in some compressed archive.
  • the files are kept for longer as they document what happened. Because some issues / warnings or situations might have gone unnoticed but raise issues later.
  • the files can help also in SAP support cases
  • the files are never deleted for above reasons or only deleted after x years or n further upgrades,...

Of some I've heard they didn't care about them, some throw them away real quick, some zip them directly after to a separate fileshare... it's wild.

Question:
Once a technical upgrade is completed - do you keep the log files created by SUM? How long? How far of reach? 
Please feel encouraged to share your experiences even if it's already listed by someone else.

Thank you

entry.title: Any Tips to Speed Up Rendering Time?
entry.content:
Hey everyone,

I’ve been diving deep into video editing recently—mostly for YouTube and a few freelance projects—and I’ve hit a major bottleneck: rendering time. Even short videos in 1080p or 4K are taking an unusually long time to export, sometimes 30–45 minutes depending on the effects, transitions, and grading involved.

I’m currently editing with [insert your editor—e.g., Adobe Premiere Pro or DaVinci Resolve] on a decent mid-range setup (16 GB RAM, Ryzen 5, GTX 1660), but I feel like the software isn’t using my system efficiently. Before I look at hardware upgrades, I wanted to check in here for some practical advice.

Here are a few questions I have:

  • Are there render settings or formats I can tweak to speed up the process without heavily sacrificing quality?

  • I’ve heard of proxy editing—does it affect final render time or just smooth the workflow during editing?

  • How important is hardware acceleration, and how do I enable it correctly for my setup?

  • Are there better codecs or formats for faster rendering, especially for platforms like YouTube?

  • Would a dedicated rendering plugin help?

  • Should I be closing all background apps while exporting?

Also, I’ve seen some newer tools developed by video editing app development companies that claim faster rendering using AI or GPU optimization. Has anyone tried one of these newer editors or apps?

I’d appreciate any advice—even a few saved minutes per project would mean a lot over time. Thanks in advance, and looking forward to your tips!

entry.title: Error stop occurred during SAP package import (tcode: SPAM) at AUTO_MOD_SPAU phase.
entry.content:
An error stop occurred during the package import process in SAP (transaction code: SPAM) at the AUTO_MOD_SPAU phase.

 

- Env.

SPAM 7.40/0081

 

- Target Components and Versions

SAP_BASIS: SAPKB74029 → SAPKB74030

SAP_GWFND: SAPK-74029INSAPGWFND → SAPK-74030INSAPGWFND

 

SPAM status: Error stop

Import Phase: AUTO_MOD_SPAU

 

During the import process to version 74030, a Runtime Error: DBSQL_INTERNAL_ERROR occurred.

I retried the import using the “Ignore General Error” option, but it stopped again at the same point.

 

The displayed message is as follows:

The termination occurred in the ABAP program "SAPRUPGM", in the routine "SELECT_DELETED_OBJECTS".
The main program was "SAPRUPRM".
